“Balancing Demands at the Food-Water-Energy Nexus”
Dr. Sue Carter
Associate Professor of Physics, Physics Department, UC Santa Cruz

The growth of the world population towards 10 billion over the next 50 years will significantly increase the demand for food, water and energy, but these 3 necessities are frequently in competition with each other. In this talk, I’ll discuss a pathway forward for balancing these 3 critical resources, while preserving our other natural resources and reducing the impacts of climate change.

The Vikings Exhibition: Interactive Exhibits, Artifacts & More -- Final Weeks

Viking culture comes alive as the largest collection of Viking artifacts ever displayed in North America invades Discovery Times Square. Nab these tickets in the exhibition's final weeks and skip the line, heading straight to the more than 500 treasures on display, including jewelry, swords and armor, and pagan religious iconography. Hands-on interactive activities put you in the daily life of the Vikings. Compete in authentic Viking games and test your strength with a reproduction of a Viking sword. Then take in the craftsmanship of full-scale models of Viking ships. With artifacts that have never been seen outside of Scandinavia, The Vikings Exhibition will have you feeling like a real Viking.

Elementary Choir- Students in third through fifth grade will enjoy a variety of activities including singing and small group offerings. event.description: Master cellist Ma conceived the Silk Road Ensemble in 2000 as an international collective of musicians from different Eurasian cultures that would explore the power of music to transcend boundaries — as Ma puts it, “Musicians coming together to see what happens when strangers meet.” The group of fifty or so artists has since produced seven acclaimed albums and performed before over two million people in 33 countries. Oscar-winning filmmaker Neville (TWENTY FEET FROM STARDOM) is especially adept at presenting both the music and the stories behind the music, and this enchanting documentary is no exception. It begins with a rousing open-air concert in a public square in Istanbul, then sketches in the biography of Ma (including a wonderful clip of the seven-year-old prodigy performing at the Kennedy White House) and the evolution of the Ensemble. It proceeds to interweave the back stories of selected Ensemble members (often survivors of political oppression), including Iranian exile Kayhan Kalhor, master of the kamancheh, or Persian spiked fiddle, and Cristina Pato, a green-haired. rock-starlike bagpiper known as “the Jimi Hendrix of Galicia.” DCP digital. (MR)
event.title: The Music of Strangers: Yo-Yo Ma & The Silk Road Ensemble
